    <h2 id="science">The Science of Collagen and Skin Aging</h2>

    <p>Collagen is the most abundant protein in the human body, constituting 75-80% of the dry weight of skin. In the dermis (the structural layer beneath the visible epidermis), collagen fibers form a dense, cross-linked matrix that provides tensile strength, elasticity, and hydration retention. When this matrix degrades — through aging, UV exposure, and oxidative stress — the visible result is wrinkles, sagging, and thin, fragile skin.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">1%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of dermal collagen is lost <strong>every year</strong> after age 30, according to research published in the <em>American Journal of Pathology</em>. By age 50, the average person has lost 25-30% of their skin collagen. By 70, that number reaches 50%. This progressive loss is the primary driver of visible skin aging — more significant than sun damage, smoking, or environmental factors combined.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The question is whether oral collagen supplementation — taking collagen peptides by mouth — can actually reach the dermis and stimulate new collagen production. The answer, based on a growing body of clinical evidence, is yes. Hydrolyzed collagen peptides are absorbed in the small intestine, enter the bloodstream as di- and tri-peptides (particularly prolyl-hydroxyproline and hydroxyprolyl-glycine), and accumulate in the skin where they act as both building blocks and signaling molecules that stimulate fibroblast activity.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2019 meta-analysis published in the <em>Journal of Drugs in Dermatology</em> analyzed <strong>11 randomized controlled trials with 805 participants</strong> and concluded that oral collagen supplementation significantly improved skin elasticity, hydration, and dermal collagen density compared to placebo. The mean improvement in skin hydration was 9% and skin elasticity improved by 5-7% over 4-12 weeks of supplementation at doses of 2.5-10 grams daily.</p>
      <cite>Journal of Drugs in Dermatology, 2019 — Meta-analysis of 11 RCTs (n=805)</cite>
    </div>

